# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-prores
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] 3GP is defined in the ETSI 3GPP technical specification.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] 3G2 is defined in the 3GPP2 technical specification.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] The 3GP and 3G2 file formats are both structurally based on the ISO base media file format defined in ISO/IEC 14496-12 – MPEG-4 Part 12, but older versions of the 3GP file format did not use some of its features.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] 3GP and 3G2 are container formats similar to MPEG-4 Part 14 (MP4), which is also based on MPEG-4 Part 12.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] The 3GP and 3G2 file format were designed to decrease storage and bandwidth requirements to accommodate mobile phones.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] They are good for lower end smartphones for faster streaming & download.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] Some cell phones use the `.mp4` extension for 3GP video.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] The 3GP file format stores video streams as MPEG-4 Part 2, H.263, or MPEG-4 Part 10 (AVC/H.264), and audio streams as AMR-NB, AMR-WB, AMR-WB+, AAC-LC, HE-AAC v1 or Enhanced aacPlus (HE-AAC v2).
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] 3GPP allowed use of AMR and H.263 codecs in the ISO base media file format (MPEG-4 Part 12), because 3GPP specified the usage of the Sample Entry and template fields in the ISO base media file format as well as defining new boxes to which codecs refer.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] These extensions were registered by the registration authority for code-points in ISO base media file format ("MP4 Family" files).
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] For the storage of MPEG-4 media specific information in 3GP files, the 3GP specification refers to MP4 and the AVC file format, which are also based on the ISO base media file format.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] The MP4 and the AVC file format specifications described usage of MPEG-4 content in the ISO base media file format.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] A 3GP file is always big-endian, storing and transferring the most significant bytes first.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] The 3G2 file format can store the same video streams and most of the audio streams used in the 2007 3GP file format.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] In addition, 3G2 stores audio streams as EVRC, EVRC-B, EVRC-WB, 13K (QCELP), SMV or VMR-WB, which was specified by 3GPP2 for use in ISO base media file format.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] The 3G2 specification also defined some enhancements to 3GPP Timed Text.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] 3G2 file format does not store Enhanced aacPlus (HE-AAC v2) and AMR-WB+ audio streams.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] For the storage of MPEG-4 media (AAC audio, MPEG-4 Part 2 video, MPEG-4 Part 10 – H.264/AVC) in 3G2 files, the 3G2 specification refers to the MP4 file format and the AVC file format specification, which described usage of this content in the ISO base media file format.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] For the storage of H.263 and AMR content 3G2 specification refers to the 3GP file format specification.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] When transferred to a computer, 3GP movies can be viewed on Microsoft Windows, Apple macOS, and the various Linux-based operating systems; on the former two with Windows Media Player and Apple QuickTime respectively (their built-in media players), and on all three with VLC media player.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] Programs such as Media Player Classic, K-Multimedia Player, Totem, RealPlayer, MPlayer, and GOM Player can also be used.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] 3GP and 3G2 files can be encoded and decoded with open source software FFmpeg.
[src:apple-prores/3gp-and-3g2] Media tags can be read and written on Linux, macOS and Windows using the open source AtomicParsley command-line utility.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The **3rd Generation Partnership Project** (**3GPP**) is an umbrella term for a number of standards organizations which develop protocols for mobile telecommunications.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] 3GPP is a partnership project whose partners are its Organizational Partners (OPs), which are seven national or regional telecommunication standards organizations, and its Market Representation Partners (MRPs), which are a variety of other organizations.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] 3GPP organizes its work into three different streams: Radio Access Networks (TSG RAN), Services and Systems Aspects (TSG SA), and Core Network and Terminals (TSG CT).
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The project was established in December 1998 with the goal of developing a specification for a 3G mobile phone system based on the 2G GSM system, within the scope of the International Telecommunication Union's International Mobile Telecommunications-2000, hence the name 3GPP.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] It should not be confused with now discontinued 3rd Generation Partnership Project 2 (3GPP2), which shadowed the 3GPP work to continue the development of a competing 3G system, CDMA2000.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The 3GPP administrative support team (known as the "Mobile Competence Centre") is located at the European Telecommunications Standards Institute headquarters in the Sophia Antipolis technology park in France.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The seven 3GPP Organizational Partners are from Asia, Europe and North America.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] 3GPP standards are structured as *Releases*.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Discussion of 3GPP thus frequently refers to the functionality in one release or another.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Each release incorporates hundreds of individual technical specification and technical report documents, each of which may have been through many revisions.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Current 3GPP standards incorporate the latest revision of the GSM standards.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The documents are made available without charge on 3GPP's web site.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The technical specifications cover not only the radio part ("*air interface*") and core network, but also billing information and speech coding down to source code level.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Cryptographic aspects (such as authentication, confidentiality) are also specified.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The 3GPP specification work is done in Technical Specification Groups (TSGs) and Working Groups (WGs).
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The closure of GERAN was announced in January 2016.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The specification work on legacy GSM/EDGE system was transferred to RAN WG, RAN6.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The 3GPP structure also includes a Project Coordination Group, which is the highest decision-making body.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Its missions include the management of overall timeframe and work progress.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] 3GPP standardization work is contribution-driven.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Companies ("individual members") participate through their membership to a 3GPP organizational partner.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] As of December 2020, 3GPP is composed of 719 individual members.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Test specifications are sometimes defined as stage 4, as they follow stage 3.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Specifications are grouped into releases.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] A release consists of a set of internally consistent set of features and specifications.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Timeframes are defined for each release by specifying freezing dates.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Once a release is frozen, only essential corrections are allowed (i.e. addition and modifications of functions are forbidden).
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] Freezing dates are defined for each stage.
[src:apple-prores/3gpp] The 3GPP specifications are transposed into deliverables by the organizational partners.
[src:apple-prores/3ivx] Official decoders and encoders were provided for Microsoft Windows, Mac OS, BeOS, Amiga and Linux.
[src:apple-prores/3ivx] In addition, FFmpeg can decode 3ivx encoded video.
[src:apple-prores/3ivx] The company was notable for its support of the Haiku OS, providing a port of the 3ivx codec.
[src:apple-prores/3ivx] The 3ivx port maintainer also produced a QuickTime MOV extractor and an MPEG-4 extractor for Haiku.
[src:apple-prores/3ivx] 3ivx developed an HTTP Live Streaming Client SDK for Windows 8 and Windows 8 Phones for the playback of HLS content on in Windows 8 Modern UI apps.
[src:apple-prores/3ivx] As of 2019, the 3ivx codec was no longer available for purchase from their website.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The 4K television market share increased as prices fell dramatically throughout 2013 and 2014.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The term **4K** is generic and refers to any resolution with a horizontal pixel count of approximately 4,000.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Several different 4K resolutions have been standardized by various organizations.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] 4K resolution is approximately 8 million pixels, which is 4 times as many as 1080p.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2005, Digital Cinema Initiatives (DCI), a prominent standards organization in the cinema industry, published the **Digital Cinema System Specification**.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This specification establishes standardized 2K and 4K container formats for digital cinema production, with resolutions of 2048 × 1080 and 4096 × 2160 respectively.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] 2K distributions can have a frame rate of either 24 or 48 FPS, while 4K distributions must have a frame rate of 24 FPS.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Some articles claim that the terms **2K** and **4K** were coined by DCI and refer exclusively to the 2K and 4K formats defined in the DCI standard.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] However, usage of these terms in the cinema industry predates the publication of the DCI standard, and they are generally understood as casual terms for any resolution approximately 2000 or 4000 pixels in width, rather than names for specific standard resolutions.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2007, the Society of Motion Picture and Television Engineers published *SMPTE ST 2036-1*, which defines parameters for two UHDTV systems called **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2**.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2012, the International Telecommunication Union, Radiocommunication Sector published Recommendation BT.2020, also known as the Ultra High Definition Television (UHDTV) standard.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] It adopts the same image parameters defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Although the UHDTV standard does not define any official names for the formats it defines, ITU typically uses the terms **4K**, **4K UHD**, or **4K UHDTV** to refer to the 3840 × 2160 system in public announcements and press releases (**8K** for the 7680 × 4320 system).
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In some of ITU's other standards documents, the terms **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2** are used as shorthand.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In October 2012, the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) announced its definition of the term **Ultra High-Definition** (or **Ultra HD**) for use with marketing consumer display devices.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The CEA definition does allow manufacturers to use other terms—such as **4K**—alongside the Ultra HD logo.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Since the resolution in CEA's definition is only a minimum requirement, displays with higher resolutions such as 4096 × 2160 or 5120 × 2880 also qualify as "Ultra HD" displays, provided they meet the other requirements.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Some 4K resolutions, like 3840 × 2160, are often casually referred to as **2160p**.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The term **2160p** could be applied to any format with a height of 2160 pixels, but it is most commonly used in reference to the 4K UHDTV resolution of 3840 × 2160 due to its association with the well-known 720p and 1080p HDTV formats.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Although 3840 × 2160 is both a 4K resolution and a 2160p resolution, these terms cannot always be used interchangeably since not all 4K resolutions are 2160 pixels tall, and not all 2160p resolutions are ≈4000 pixels wide.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] However, some companies have begun using the term "4K" to describe devices with support for a 2160p resolution, even if it is not close to 4000 pixels wide.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] For example, many "4K" dash cams only support a resolution of 2880 × 2160 (4∶3); although this is a 2160p resolution, it is not a 4K resolution.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Conversely, Samsung released a 5120 × 2160 (64∶27) TV, but marketed it as a "4K" TV despite its 5K-class resolution.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2015, LG Display announced the implementation of a new technology called M+, which is the addition of white subpixels along with the regular RGB dots in their IPS panel technology.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The media and internet users later called this "RGBW" TVs because of the white sub pixel.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Most of the new M+ technology was employed on 4K TV sets, which led to a controversy after tests showed that the addition of a white subpixel replacing the traditional RGB structure would reduce the resolution by around 25%.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] After tests done by Intertek in which the technical aspects of LG M+ TVs were analyzed and they concluded that "the addressable resolution display is 2,880 X 2,160 for each red, green, blue", in other words, the LG TVs were technically 2.8K as it became known in the controversy.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This negatively impacts the rendering of text, making it a bit fuzzier, which is especially noticeable when a TV is used as a PC monitor.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2019, Sony was granted the CinemaWide trademark by the European Union Intellectual Property Office (EUIPO), in which the trademark covers 'Class 9' electronic devices, including smartphones.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Sony Xperia smartphones are the most widely known products that equipped with CinemaWide 4K display, such as Xperia 1, Xperia 1 II, Xperia 1 III, Xperia 1 IV and Xperia 1 V.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Video sharing website YouTube and the television industry have adopted 3840 × 2160 as their 4K standard.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] As of 2014, 4K content from major broadcasters remained limited.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] By late 2014, 4K content was becoming more widely available online, including on Apple TV, YouTube, Netflix, Hulu, and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] By 2013, some UHDTV models were available to general consumers in the range of US$600.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] As of 2015, prices on smaller computer and television panels had dropped below US$400.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] On March 26, 2013, the Advanced Television Systems Committee announced new proposals of a new standard called ATSC 3.0 which would implement UHD broadcasts at resolutions of up to 3840 × 2160 or 7680 × 4320.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The standard would also include framerates of up to 120 Hz, HEVC encoding, wide color gamut, as well as high dynamic range.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2014, the Digital Video Broadcasting Project released a new set of standards intended to guide the implementation of high-resolution content in broadcast television.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Dubbed **DVB-UHDTV**, it establishes two standards, known as **UHD-1** (for 4K content) and **UHD-2** (for 8K content).
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] These standards use resolutions of 3840 × 2160 and 7680 × 4320 respectively, with framerates of up to 60 Hz, color depth up to 10 bpc (30 bit/px), and HEVC encoding for transmission.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] DVB is currently focusing on the implementation of the UHD-1 standard.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] DVB finalized **UHD-1 Phase 2** in 2016, with the introduction of service by broadcasters expected in 2017.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] UHD-1 Phase 2 adds features such as high dynamic range (using HLG and PQ at 10 or 12 bits), wide color gamut (BT.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] As of February 2025, both YouTube and Vimeo support high-resolution video uploads, with maximum resolutions of 4096 × 2304 pixels (approximately 9.4 megapixels) and 4096 × 2160 pixels (approximately 8.8 megapixels), respectively.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The growing availability of 4K content across streaming platforms like Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, and YouTube has made it more accessible to consumers.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Vimeo's 4K content is currently limited to mostly nature documentaries and tech coverage.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC or H.265) facilitates streaming of 4K content at bitrates between 20 and 30 Mbit/s, offering efficient compression without significant quality loss.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In January 2014, Naughty America launched the first adult video service streaming in 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In February 2025, Super Bowl LIX was broadcast in 4K resolution with Dolby Vision HDR and Dolby Atmos sound for the first time.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Fox aired the game, and it was also available for free streaming in 4K on Tubi, marking a significant milestone in sports broadcasting.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The first mobile phones to be able to record at 2160p (3840 × 2160) were released in late 2013, including the Samsung Galaxy Note 3, which is able to record 2160p at 30 frames per second.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In the year 2014, the OnePlus One was released with the option to record DCI 4K (4096 × 2160) at 24 frames per second, as well as LG G3 and Samsung Galaxy Note 4 with optical image stabilization.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In the year 2015, Apple announced the iPhone 6s was released with the 12 megapixel camera that has the option to record 4K at 25 or 30 frames per second.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In the years 2017 and 2018, mobile phone chipsets reached sufficient processing power that mobile phone vendors started releasing mobile phones that allow recording 2160p footage at 60 frames per second for a smoother and more realistic appearance.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] iMac with Retina Display (2014) is one of the earliest computers that utilise 4K widescreen.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 1981, the NEC μPD7220 computer graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×1024p (progressive scan) or 4096×2048i (interlaced).
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 1984, Hitachi's ARTC HD63484 graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×2048p (progressive scan) or 4096×4096i (interlaced), targeted at the bit-mapped desktop publishing market.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2000, JVC introduced the first 4K digital cinema video projector using D-ILA technology.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The first commercially available 4K camera for cinematographic purposes was the Dalsa Origin, released in 2003.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Sony began offering 4K digital cinema projectors in 2004.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] 4K digital projectors were introduced to movie theaters in 2005, but most theaters continued using analog movie projectors until 4K digital projectors eventually replaced them by 2011.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] 4K streaming technology was developed during the mid-to-late 2000s by several research groups in universities around the world, such as University of California, San Diego, CALIT2, Keio University and Naval Postgraduate School.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] They realized several demonstrations in venues such as IGrid in 2004 and CineGrid.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] YouTube began supporting 4K for video uploads in 2010 as a result of leading manufacturers producing 4K cameras.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Users could view 4K video by selecting "Original" from the quality settings until December 2013, when the 2160p option appeared in the quality menu.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In November 2013, YouTube began to use the VP9 video compression standard, saying that it was more suitable for 4K than High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC).
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Google, which owns YouTube, developed VP9.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The first 4K home theater projector was released by Sony in 2012.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Despite this, as of 2023, there are not many finished films with 4K resolution.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Even for movies and TV shows shot using 6K or 8K cameras, almost all finished films are edited in HD resolution and enlarged to fit a 4K format.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Sony is one of the leading studios promoting UHDTV content, as of 2013 offering a little over 70 movie and television titles via digital download to a specialized player that stores and decodes the video.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The large files (≈40 GB), distributed through consumer broadband connections, raise concerns about data caps.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2014, Netflix began streaming *House of Cards*, *Breaking Bad*, and "some nature documentaries" at 4K to compatible televisions with an HEVC decoder.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Most 4K televisions sold in 2013 did not natively support HEVC, with most major manufacturers announcing support in 2014.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Amazon Studios began shooting their full-length original series and new pilots with 4K resolution in 2014.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] They are now currently available through Amazon Video.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In March 2016 the first players and discs for Ultra HD Blu-ray—a physical optical disc format supporting 4K resolution and high-dynamic-range video (HDR) at 60 frames per second—were released.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] On August 2, 2016, Microsoft released the Xbox One S, which supports 4K streaming and has an Ultra HD Blu-ray disc drive, but does not support 4K gaming.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] On November 10, 2016, Sony released the PlayStation 4 Pro, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though many games use checkerboard rendering or are upscaled 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] On November 7, 2017, Microsoft released the Xbox One X, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though not all games are rendered at native 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Though the price of home cinema viewing devices began to drop rapidly from 2013, the digital video projector market saw limited expansion as very few manufacturers had fully 4K-capable lineups.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Native 4K projectors remained priced in the five-figure range well into 2015, only falling below US$10,000 later that year.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Sony was the sole major manufacturer offering a comprehensive 4K projection solution as of 2015.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Critics argue that, at typical direct-view panel sizes and viewing distances, the extra pixels of 4K are unnecessary for normal human vision.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In contrast, home cinema projectors use larger screens without necessarily increasing the viewing distance to match the scale.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This technology reached its fourth generation in 2016.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] JVC applied this technology to create an 8K flight simulation system for Boeing, meeting the visual acuity limits of 20/25.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The first pixel-shifted 4K UHD projectors adopted by the market are Optoma, BenQ, Dell, et al., for those adopt a 2718×1528 pixel structure.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The amount of data these projectors process is true 4K, but they overlap the pixels, which is what pixel shifting is.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In fact, each of those pixels is far larger.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In fact, each one has 50% more area than true 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This way, they project a pixel and shift it up to the right by a half diameter and project it again with modified data—the second pixel overlaid on the first.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This would result in adjacent red and green pixels effectively forming yellow, with a fringe on one side of red, on the other of green—except that the fringe takes on another color as the next line of pixels overlaps too.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] 4K UHD or 1080p pixel shifting cannot reveal the fine detail of a true 4K projector such as those Sony ships in the business, education, and home markets.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] While projecting UHD, it might look as though the pixel structures would have 1/4 the area of 1080p; it just doesn't happen with pixel shifting.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] That much resolution is only carried by a true 4K projector.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This is why "true" 4K costs so much more than 4K UHD projectors that have more or less similar feature sets.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] They produce smaller pixels, finer resolution—no loss of detail or color from the overlapping pixels.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This is in stark contrast to the small variation in the aspect ratio difference, which would be capable of being noticeable in a few companies, such as Kaleidescape, offering media servers that enable 4K UHD Blu-ray movies with a wide dynamic range in a home theater.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In November 2014, American satellite provider DirecTV (owned by AT&T) became the first pay-TV provider to offer access to 4K content, although limited to selected video-on-demand films.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In August 2015, British sports network BT Sport launched a 4K feed, with its first broadcast being the 2015 FA Community Shield football match.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Two production units were used, producing the traditional broadcast in high-definition, and a separate 4K broadcast.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] As the network did not want to mix 4K footage with upconverted HD footage, this telecast did not feature traditional studio segments at pre-game or half-time, but those hosted from the stadium by the match commentators using a 4K camera.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] BT envisioned that if viewers wanted to watch studio analysis, they would switch to the HD broadcast and then back for the game.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Footage was compressed using H.264 encoders and transmitted to BT Tower, where it was then transmitted back to BT Sport studios and decompressed for distribution, via 4K-compatible BT TV set-top boxes on an eligible BT Infinity internet plan with at least a 25 Mbit/s connection.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In late 2015 and January 2016, three of Canada's television providers – including Quebec-based Vidéotron, Ontario-based Rogers Cable, and Bell Fibe TV, announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes that can stream 4K content to subscribers over gigabit internet service.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Bell Media announced via its TSN division a slate of 4K telecasts to begin on January 20, 2016, including selected Toronto Raptors games and regional NHL games.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] On January 14, 2016, in cooperation with BT Sport, Sportsnet broadcast the first ever NBA game produced in 4K – a Toronto Raptors/Orlando Magic game at O2 Arena in London, England.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] On January 20, also during a Raptors game, TSN presented the first live 4K telecast produced in North America.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Three days later, Sportsnet presented the first NHL game in 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] For the opening game of the 2016 Toronto Blue Jays season, Dome constructed "Trillium" – a production truck integrating both 4K and 1080i high-definition units.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Bell Media's CTV also broadcast the 2016 Juno Awards in 4K as the first awards show presented in the format.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In February 2016, Spanish-language Univision trialed 4K by producing a closed-circuit TV broadcast of a football friendly between the national teams of Mexico and Senegal from Miami (America) in the format.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The broadcast was streamed privately to several special viewing locations.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Univision aimed to develop a 4K streaming app to publicly televise the final of Copa América Centenario in 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In March 2016, DirecTV and CBS Sports announced that they would produce the "Amen Corner" supplemental coverage from the Masters golf tournament in 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In late 2016, Telus TV announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] After having trialed the technology in limited matches at the 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup, and the 2014 FIFA World Cup (via private tests and public viewings in the host city of Rio de Janeiro), the 2018 FIFA World Cup was the first FIFA World Cup in which all matches were produced in 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Host Broadcasting Services stated that at least 75% of the broadcast cut on each match would come from 4K cameras (covering the majority of main angles), with instant replays and some camera angles being upconverted from 1080p sources.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] These broadcasts were made available from selected rightsholders, such as the BBC in the UK, and selected television providers in the United States.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Technical limitations in distributing 4K broadcasts (including the increased cost of 4K-compatible production equipment) have led to some broadcasters deciding against the format in favour of emphasizing 1080p/HDR broadcasts instead.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] After having broadcast UEFA Euro and the Champions League final in the format, UEFA discontinued 4K coverage for both in 2024, as broadcasters elected to put resources behind HDR and other on-air features instead.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Some U.S. broadcasters, such as CBS Sports, Fox Sports, and USA Network have broadcast events promoted as having "4K" feeds, but are actually 1080p/HDR broadcasts upconverted to 4K.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] For the 2024 Summer Olympics, USA Network's "4K" coverage was sourced from host broadcaster Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS) in 4K, but downconverted to 1080p when received by NBC Sports' studios, and then upconverted to 4K for distribution.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 is the dominant 4K resolution in the consumer media and display industries.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This is the resolution of the UHDTV1 format defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1, as well as the 4K UHDTV format defined by ITU-R in Rec.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] 2020, and is also the minimum resolution for CEA's definition of **Ultra HD** displays and projectors.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 was also chosen by the DVB project for their 4K broadcasting standard, UHD-1.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This resolution has an aspect ratio of 16∶9, with 8,294,400 total pixels.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] It is exactly double the horizontal and vertical resolution of 1080p (1920 × 1080) for a total of 4 times as many pixels, and triple the horizontal and vertical resolution of 720p (1280 × 720) for a total of 9 times as many pixels.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] It is sometimes referred to as "2160p", based on the naming patterns established by the previous 720p and 1080p HDTV standards.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In 2013, televisions capable of displaying UHD resolutions were seen by consumer electronics companies as the next trigger for an upgrade cycle after a lack of consumer interest in 3D television.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This resolution is used mainly in digital cinema production, and has a total of 8,847,360 pixels with an aspect ratio of 256∶135 (≈19∶10).
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] It was standardized as the resolution of the 4K container format defined by Digital Cinema Initiatives in the Digital Cinema System specification, and is the native resolution of all DCI-compliant 4K digital projectors and monitors.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The DCI specification allows several different resolutions for the content inside the container, depending on the desired aspect ratio.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The DCI 4K standard has twice the horizontal and vertical resolution of DCI 2K (2048 × 1080), with four times as many pixels overall.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Digital movies made in 4K may be produced, scanned, or stored in a number of other resolutions depending on what storage aspect ratio is used.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] In the digital cinema production chain, a resolution of 4096 × 3112 is often used for acquiring "open gate" or anamorphic input material, a resolution based on the historical resolution of scanned Super 35 mm film.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] The main advantage of recording video at the 4K standard is that fine spatial detail is resolved well.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Individual still frames extracted from 3840×2160-pixel video footage can act as 8.3 megapixel still photographs, while only 2.1 megapixels at 1080p and 0.9 megapixels at 720p.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] If the final video resolution is reduced to 2K from a 4K recording, more detail is apparent than would have been achieved from a native 2K recording.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Increased fineness and contrast is then possible with output to DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Some cinematographers record at 4K with the Super 35 film format to offset any resolution loss that may occur during video processing.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Many consumer electronics such as mobile phones store video footage in Y′CBCR format with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling, which records color information at only one quarter the resolution as the brightness information.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] For 3840 × 2160 video, this means that the color information is only stored at 1920 × 1080.
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] Consumer cameras and mobile phones record 2160p footage at much higher bit rates (usually 50 to 100 Mbit/s) than 1080p (usually 10 to 30 Mbit/s).
[src:apple-prores/4k-resolution] This higher bit rate reduces the visibility of compression artifacts, even if viewed on monitors with a lower resolution than 2160p.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The program can be used from a Windows graphical user interface that also features shell integration, or from a command-line interface as the command `7z` that offers cross-platform support (see versions for details).
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] An obsolete port of 7-Zip to POSIX systems was called `p7zip`.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Most of the 7-Zip source code is under the LGPL-2.1-or-later license; the unRAR code, however, is under the LGPL-2.1-or-later license with an "unRAR restriction", which states that developers are not permitted to use the code to reverse-engineer the RAR compression algorithm.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Since version 21.01 alpha, native Linux support has been added.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] By default, 7-Zip creates 7z-format archives with a `.7z` file extension.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Each archive can contain multiple directories and files.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] As a *container* format, security or size reduction are achieved by looking for similarities throughout the data using a stacked combination of filters.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] These can consist of pre-processors, compression algorithms, and encryption filters.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The core 7z compression uses a variety of algorithms, the most common of which are bzip2, PPMd, LZMA2, and LZMA.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Developed by Pavlov, LZMA is a relatively new system, making its debut as part of the 7z format.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] LZMA uses an LZ-based sliding dictionary of up to 3840 MB in size, backed by a range coder.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The native 7z file format is open and modular.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The 7z file format specification is distributed with the program's source code, in the "doc" sub-directory.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-Zip supports a number of other compression and non-compression archive formats (both for packing and unpacking), including ZIP, gzip, bzip2, xz, tar, and WIM.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The utility also supports unpacking APM, ar, ARJ, chm, cpio, deb, FLV, JAR, LHA/LZH, LZMA, MSLZ, Office Open XML, onepkg, RAR, RPM, SMZIP, SWF, XAR, and Z archives and cramfs, DMG, FAT, HFS, ISO, MBR, NTFS, SquashFS, UDF, and VHD disk images.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-Zip supports the ZIPX format for unpacking only.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] It has had this support since at least version 9.20, which was released in late 2010.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-Zip can open some MSI files, allowing access to the meta-files within along with the main contents.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Some Microsoft CAB (LZX compression) and NSIS (LZMA) installer formats can be opened.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Similarly, some Microsoft executable programs (.EXEs) that are self-extracting archives or otherwise contain archived content (e.g., some setup files) may be opened as archives.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] When compressing ZIP or gzip files, 7-Zip uses its own DEFLATE encoder, which may achieve higher compression, but at lower speed, than the more common zlib DEFLATE implementation.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The 7-Zip deflate encoder implementation is available separately as part of the AdvanceCOMP suite of tools.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The decompression engine for RAR archives was developed using freely available source code of the unRAR program, which has a licensing restriction against creation of a RAR compressor.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-Zip v15.06 and later support extraction of files in the RAR5 format.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Some backup systems use formats supported by archiving programs such as 7-Zip; e.g., some Android backups are in `tar` format, and can be extracted by archivers such as 7-Zip.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-Zip comes with a file manager along with the standard archiver tools.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The file manager has a toolbar with options to create an archive, extract an archive, test an archive to detect errors, copy, move, and delete files, and open a file properties menu exclusive to 7-Zip.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The file manager, by default, displays hidden files because it does not follow Windows Explorer's policies.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The tabs show name, modification time, original and compressed sizes, attributes, and comments (4DOS `descript.ion` format).
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] When going up one directory on the root, all drives, removable or internal appear.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] A 64-bit version is available, with support for large memory maps, leading to faster compression.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] As of 2026, the application comes only with the `7z.exe` command line binary.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-zip comes with a plug-in system for expansion.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] The official "Links" page points to many plugins written by TC4Shell, providing extra file support.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-Zip has a LZMA SDK which was originally dual-licensed under both the GNU LGPL and Common Public License, with an additional special exception for linked binaries.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] On 2 December 2008, the SDK was placed by Igor Pavlov in the public domain.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Self-extracting archives created by versions of 7-Zip prior to 16.03 were vulnerable to arbitrary code execution through DLL hijacking: they load and run a DLL named UXTheme.dll, if it is in the same folder as the executable file.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] 7-Zip 16.03 release notes mention that the installer and SFX modules add protection against the DLL preloading attack.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Versions prior to 18.05 contain an arbitrary code execution vulnerability in the RAR extracting module, CVE-2018-10115.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Versions prior to 23.0 contain an arbitrary code execution vulnerability, CVE-2023-31102.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Versions prior to 24.07 are affected by a remote code execution vulnerability, CVE-2024-11477.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Versions prior to 26.01 contain an arbitrary code execution vulnerability, CVE-2026-48095.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Snapfiles.com in 2012 rated 7-Zip 4.5 stars out of 5, noting, "[its] interface and additional features are fairly basic, but the compression ratio is outstanding".
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] TechRepublic in 2009 found the detailed settings for Windows File Manager integration were "appreciated" and called the compression-decompression benchmark utility "neat".
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] Between 2002 and 2024, 7-Zip was downloaded 428 million times from SourceForge alone.
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] In 2007, SourceForge granted it community choice awards for "Technical Design" and for "Best Project".
[src:apple-prores/7-zip] In 2013, Tom's Hardware conducted a compression speed test comparing 7-Zip, MagicRAR, WinRAR, WinZip; they concluded that 7-Zip beat out all the others with regards to compression speed, ratio, and size and awarded the software the 2013 Tom's Hardware Elite award.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] 8K display resolution is the successor to 4K resolution.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] TV manufacturers pushed to make 4K a new standard by 2017.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] At CES 2012, the first prototype 8K TVs were unveiled by Japanese electronics corporation Sharp.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The feasibility of a fast transition to this new standard is questionable in view of the absence of broadcasting resources.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In 2018, Strategy Analytics predicted that 8K-ready devices will still only account for 3% of UHD TVs by 2023 with global sales of 11 million units a year.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] However, TV manufacturers remain optimistic as the 4K market grew much faster than expected, with actual sales exceeding projections nearly six-fold in 2016.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In 2013, a transmission network's capability to carry HDTV resolution was limited by internet speeds and relied on satellite broadcast to transmit the high data rates.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The demand is expected to drive the adoption of video compression standards and to place significant pressure on physical communication networks in the near future.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In 2018, few cameras had the capability to shoot video in 8K, NHK being one of the few companies to have created a small broadcasting camera with an 8K image sensor.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] By 2018, Red Digital Cinema camera company had delivered three 8K cameras in both a Full Frame sensor and Super 35 sensor.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In 1986, Sony introduced a smectic light valve LCD laser projector that could display high resolutions up to 8K resolution (8000×10,000).
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In 1995, Japan's public broadcaster NHK was the first to start research and development of 4320p resolution, with the Super Hi-Vision system intended as a successor to their Hi-Vision HDTV system.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] 8K Ultra HDTV (UHDTV) was first demonstrated by NHK, JVC and Ikegami Tsushinki researchers with the Super Hi‑Vision system in January 2003.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The format was standardized by SMPTE in October 2007.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The interface was standardized by SMPTE in August 2010 and recommended as the international standard for television by ITU-R in 2012.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Followed by public displays at electronics shows and screenings of 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi and public viewings in February 2014 and the FIFA World Cup in Brazil in June 2014 using HEVC with partners AstroDesign and Ikegami Electronics.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On January 6, 2015, the MHL Consortium announced the release of the superMHL specification which will support 8K resolution at 120 fps, 48-bit video, the Rec.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] 2020 color space, high dynamic range support, a 32-pin reversible superMHL connector, and power charging of up to 40 watts.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On March 1, 2016, the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) unveiled DisplayPort 1.4, a new format that allows the use of 8K resolution (7680 × 4320) at 60 Hz with HDRR and 32 audio channels through USB-C.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On January 4, 2017, the HDMI Forum announced HDMI 2.1 featuring support for 8K video with HDR, which will be "released early in Q2 2017".
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] 8K Association Formed at CES 2019 to Help Develop 8K Ecosystem.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In early February 2020, Samsung Electronics announced during their Unpacked event that their Samsung Galaxy S20 can video record in 8K, which uses 600 MB of storage per minute.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On April 6, 2013, Astrodesign Inc. announced the AH-4800, capable of recording 8K resolution.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In April 2015, it was announced by Red that their newly unveiled Red Weapon VV is also capable of recording 8K footage.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In October 2016, they announced two additional 8K cameras, Red Weapon 8K S35 and Red Epic-W 8K S35.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The Red Weapon Dragon VV has been discontinued as of October 7, 2017, when Red unveiled the Red Weapon Monstro VV, their fourth camera capable of shooting 8K, with additional improvements in dynamic range and noise reduction, among other features.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In May 2019, mobile phone vendors started releasing the first mobile phones with 8K video recording capabilities, such as the ZTE Nubia Red Magic 3 series.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] This is enabled by the sufficient resolution of image sensors used in mobile phones, and by the sufficient chipset performance.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] However, mobile phones with up to 5K (2880p) or 6K (3240p) video cameras have never been released.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In 2007, the original 65 mm negative of the 1992 film *Baraka* was re-scanned at 8K with a film scanner built specifically for the job at FotoKem Laboratories, and used to remaster the 2008 Blu-ray release.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] According to Grover Crisp, executive VP of restoration at Sony Pictures, the new 8K scan has such high resolution that when examined, showed a series of fine concentric lines in a pattern "reminiscent of a fingerprint" near the top of the frame.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] This was caused by the film emulsion melting and cracking in the desert heat during production.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Sony had to hire a third party to minimize or eliminate the rippling artifacts in the new restored version.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On May 17, 2013, the Franklin Institute premiered *To Space and Back*, an 8K×8K, 60 fps, 3D video running approximately 25 minutes.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] During its first run at the Fels Planetarium it was played at 4K, 60 fps.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In November 2013, NHK screened the experimental-drama short film "The Chorus" at Tokyo Film Festival which was filmed in 8K and 22.2 sound format.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On May 1, 2015, an 8K abstract computer animation was screened at the Filmatic Festival at the University of California, San Diego.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The work was created as an assignment in the VIS 40/ICAM 40 Introduction to Computing in the Arts class taught at UCSD by Associate Teaching Professor Brett Stalbaum during the winter quarter of 2015, with each student producing three hundred 8192 × 4800 pixel frames.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The work's music soundtrack was composed by Mark Matamoros.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On January 6, 2016, director James Gunn stated that the 2017 film *Guardians of the Galaxy Vol.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] 2* would be the first feature film to be shot in 8K, using the Red Weapon 8K VV.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The movie was shot with 8K cameras (and partially with 4K cameras), although the digital intermediate of the movie is in a lower resolution.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Japanese public broadcaster NHK began research and development on 8K in 1995, having spent over $1 billion on R&D since then.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Codenamed *Super Hi-Vision* (named after its old Hi-Vision analog HDTV system), NHK also was simultaneously working on the development of 22.2 channel surround sound audio.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The world's first 8K television was unveiled by Sharp at the Consumer Electronics Show (CES) in 2012.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Ultimately, about 200 hours of material from the Tokyo Olympics, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were broadcast in 8K (on the NHK BS8K channel).
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The specification for an 8K Blu-ray format was also completed by the Blu-ray Disc Association for use in Japan by December 2017.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] As of the end of 2024, there are no standalone Blu-ray players certified as 8K capable (even though PC Blu-ray drives able to read 100 GB and 128 GB discs are sold commercially), and no home video releases in 8K on physical media by any major studio.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] On December 1, 2018, NHK launched BS8K, a broadcast channel transmitting at 8K resolution.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Documentaries constitute a large part of that channel's programming.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Feature films shown in 8K on that channel include *2001: A Space Odyssey* (1968) and *My Fair Lady* (1964); in both cases, 70 mm analog prints were used as a basis for the remastered 8K version.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] New productions filmed with digital 8K cameras have also been aired in 8K on that channel; they include the Edo period drama *Kikyo – The Return* and the WWII dramas *Wife of a Spy* and *Gift of Fire*.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In Germany, the third season of *Das Boot* (a historical drama TV series set on a Nazi submarine) was made available in 8K on the Samsung TV Plus streaming service.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] In China, the state-owned CMG conglomerate launched a TV channel broadcasting at 8K resolution, known as CCTV-8K.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] Test broadcasts started in 2021 while the official launch was in 2022.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The Sony PlayStation 5 Pro generates 8K graphics and output, making it the first and only game console to do so, though as of October 2025 no full 8K games for it have publicly released.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] The GeForce RTX 3090, released in September 2020 at an MSRP of $1499, was marketed by Nvidia as the first graphics card capable of 8K 60 fps HDR gaming, recording, and streaming with ShadowPlay on PCs.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] However, only its successor, the GeForce RTX 4090, is often regarded as the first graphics card to achieve playable frame rates at 8K in many modern titles.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] This is the resolution of the **UHDTV2** format defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1, as well as the **8K UHDTV** format defined in ITU-R BT.2020.
[src:apple-prores/8k-resolution] It was also chosen by the DVB project as the resolution for their 8K broadcasting standard, **UHD-2**.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes is a line of intermediate codecs, which means they are intended for use during video editing, and not for practical end-user viewing.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] This is achieved by only using intra-frame compression, where each frame is stored independently and can be decoded with no dependencies on other frames.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] The benefit of an intermediate codec is that it offers excellent random access performance in post-production applications, and retains higher quality than end-user codecs while still requiring much less expensive disk systems compared to uncompressed video.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] It is comparable to Avid's DNxHD codec or CineForm which offer similar bitrates and are also intended to be used as intermediate codecs.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes is a DCT scalar based intra-frame-only codec and is therefore simpler to decode than distribution-oriented formats like H.264.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2018 Apple added a new "ProRes RAW" (compressed Bayer filter) to Final Cut Pro X, after Blackmagic Design implemented compressed Bayer as "CinemaDNG 3:1" and "CinemaDNG 4:1" in their cameras and DaVinci Resolve.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes supports different data rates and different resolutions.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] All ProRes422-variants use chroma subsampling of 4:2:2 at 10-bit color depth.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 and 4444 XQ samples color in the 4:4:4 schema with a color depth of 10 or 12 bits, and can optionally include an alpha channel.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 was introduced with Final Cut Studio (2009) as another in the company's line of intermediate codecs for editing material but not for final delivery.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] It shares many features with other, 422, codecs of Apple's ProRes family but provides better quality than 422 HQ in color detail.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] It has a target data rate of approximately 330 Mbit/s for 4:4:4 sources at 1920x1080 and 29.97 fps.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes 4444 XQ was introduced with Final Cut Pro X version 10.1.2 in June 2014.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] It has a target data rate of approximately 500 Mbit/s for 4:4:4 sources at 1920x1080 and 29.97 fps, and requires OS X v10.8 (Mountain Lion) or later.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In April 2018 Apple released ProRes RAW.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] It is built upon the same technology as other ProRes codecs, but is directly applied to the raw data coming from the sensor, thus delaying the debayering process to the post-production stage.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes RAW therefore aims at quality and better color reproduction, rather than performance.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] Apple ProRes RAW is available in LUMIX cameras, Nikon cameras (Z9, Z8, Z6iii), Sony Alpha FX3 via Atomos Ninja V, and as of September 2025, in the Apple iPhone 17 Pro and ProMax.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes RAW is a 16 bit uncompressed video format in .mov.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In the Sony FX3 and the Atomos Ninja V, ProRes Raw records in 16 bit and compresses in 12 bit for color data.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes RAW codec is natively available in Adobe Premiere Pro, Adobe After Effects, Assimilate Scratch, Apple Final Cut Pro and Davinci Resolve.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On 28 August 2008, Apple introduced a free ProRes QuickTime Decoder for both Mac and Windows that allows playback of ProRes files through QuickTime.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On 15 September 2011, FFmpeg introduced a free decoder for ProRes 422 for libavcodec.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] FFmbc, a fork of FFmpeg customized for broadcast and professional usage, supports ProRes 422 and 4444 files.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On 1 October 2011, JCodec introduced an open source (FreeBSD License) pure Java decoder for ProRes 422, a translation of the FFmpeg version.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] Installing Final Cut Pro will install the ProRes codecs for encoding files on macOS.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] Without Final Cut Pro installed, QuickTime Player can also be used to capture ProRes 422 video from any compatible attached camera, using the "Maximum" quality setting when producing a Movie Recording.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] Apple released ProRes bundled with other pro codecs as a download for users with "qualifying copies of Final Cut Pro, Motion, or Compressor" installed, for OS X with QuickTime 7.6 and newer.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] At the April 2010 NAB Show, Digital Video Systems launched the first Windows 7 platform with the ability to encode to all the varieties of Apple ProRes at speeds far faster than real time on their Clipster product.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On March 31, 2011, Telestream added support for ProRes encoding on Windows systems with Episode Engine, Vantage, and FlipFactory as a free upgrade to the current versions of these products.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] The system must be running on Windows Server 2008 and be able to support this feature.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes video capturing and output to tape is available in Telestream's Pipeline network encoder.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On 29 October 2011, FFmpeg introduced a free encoder, enabling ProRes 422 encoding on all FFmpeg supported platforms.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On 1 November 2011, JCodec introduced an open source (BSD License) pure Java encoder for ProRes 422.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] At the April 2012 NAB Show, Brevity introduced a customized algorithm for the accelerated transport and encoding of ProRes files.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] The Arri Alexa has a built-in ProRes recording unit for its 1080p and 2K video streams, supporting ProRes 4444 and all ProRes 422 versions.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] At NAB 2012, Blackmagic announced ProRes recording support for their HyperDeck SSD recorders as well as onboard recording on the Blackmagic Cinema Camera, and Brevity announced a GPU-based ProRes transcoder with simultaneous accelerated file transport.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2013 Blackmagic Design released the Blackmagic Cinema Camera that record in RAW and ProRes files directly in camera 4:2:2 10-bit.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2013 Convergent Design introduced their Odyssey7 and Odyssey7Q monitor/recorders that can record in Apple ProRes 422 (HQ) and are certified by Apple.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2014 Atomos introduced their latest advanced recorder Shogun that can record 4K in Apple ProRes.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2015 AJA introduced the CION production camera that can capture 4K/UltraHD/2K/HD to all Apple ProRes 422 formats as well as Apple ProRes 4444 in 12-bit.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2016 Blackmagic Design released UrsaMini 4.6k that can capture from 4.6k to HD in all Apple ProRes flavor from Proxy to 4444 in 12-bit.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2018/2019 Blackmagic Design released Pocket Cinema Camera 4K that can capture 4k/UltraHD/1080p in all Apple ProRes 422 formats.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2019 Mac Pro introduced a new "Apple Afterburner" card as an optional component to accelerate ProRes and ProRes RAW decoding.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2021, Apple announced the iPhone 13 Pro, with ProRes encoding/decoding using its built-in camera app alongside its recent addition of DNG raw photos (DNG v5.1) on the 12 Pro Models.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] ProRes encoding can be performed at up to 3840 × 2160 30p ProRes HQ with Dolby Vision HDR color profiles on models with at least 256 GB of storage, while the 128 GB model will be limited to 1080p 30p with its built-in camera application.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2023, Apple announced the iPhone 15 Pro, which added the ability to shoot ProRes in the Apple Log format, as well as the ability to shoot ProRes footage at up to 3840 x 2160 60p to an external drive via the USB-C port from the built-in camera application.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In 2021, Apple announced the Apple M1 Pro and M1 Max, variants of the Apple M1 system on a chip containing, among other new features, hardware ProRes encoding and decoding acceleration.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] In February 2022, Panasonic released the Lumix GH6 mirrorless camera which has the ability to record 5.7K video in ProRes 422 HQ.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On June 6, 2022, Apple announced the Apple M2 with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On January 17, 2023, Apple announced the Apple M2 Pro and M2 Max with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] On October 30, 2023, Apple announced the Apple M3 series of chips with 8K ProRes hardware decoding and encoding acceleration.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] Lasergraphics motion picture film scanning systems include support for output to ProRes 4444 HQ/XQ, ProRes 422, and others.
[src:apple-prores/apple-prores] The ProRes codec was awarded an Engineering Emmy Award in 2020 for "Outstanding Achievement in Technology".
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV container format is a modification of the MPEG-2 transport stream (ITU-T H.222.0 | ISO/IEC 13818-1) specification for random-access media, such as Blu-ray discs, DVDs, hard drives or solid-state memory cards.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] In order to optimize the storage size, the format uses variable rate Transport Streams instead of the constant rates found in MPEG-2 TS broadcast.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] To be able to reconstruct a T-STD compliant constant rate Transport Stream for playback, the arrival timestamp of each packet needs to be recorded.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The standard MPEG-2 TS 188-byte packet is prefixed with a 4-byte extra header to a total size of 192 bytes.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The header consists of a 2-bit copy permission indicator and the 30-bit arrival timestamp with a resolution of 27 MHz.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV container format (`.m2ts`) is a standard used on Blu-ray discs.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Blu-ray disc titles authored with menu support are in the BDMV (Blu-ray disc Movie) format and contain audio, video, and other streams in a BDAV container (`.m2ts`), which is based on the MPEG transport stream format.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV container is also used in the BDAV (Blu-ray disc Audio/Visual) disc format, the consumer-oriented alternative to the BDMV discs.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV disc format is used on BD-RE and BD-R discs for audio/video recording.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV container with filename extension .MTS or .m2ts is also used in AVCHD format, which is a high-definition digital video camera recorder format.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] AVCHD is a simpler form of the Blu-ray disc standard with just one video encoding algorithm and two audio encodings.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Compared to Blu-ray disc format, AVCHD can use various storage media, such as DVD media, memory cards or hard disk drives.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV container contains videos recorded using AVCHD camcorders, such as Sony's HDR-SR(xx) series models.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Panasonic, Canon and other brands of AVCHD camcorders also store recorded video in the BDAV container format.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV container format used on Blu-ray discs can contain one of the three mandatory supported video compression formats–H.262/MPEG-2 Part 2, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC or SMPTE VC-1–and audio compression formats, such as Dolby Digital, DTS or uncompressed Linear PCM.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Optionally supported audio formats are Dolby Digital Plus, DTS-HD High Resolution Audio, DTS-HD Master Audio and Dolby TrueHD.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The BDAV container format used on AVCHD equipment is more restricted and can contain only H.264/MPEG-4 AVC video compression and Dolby Digital (AC-3) audio compression or uncompressed LPCM audio.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The names of M2TS files are in the form zzzzz.m2ts, where *zzzzz* is a five-digit number corresponding to the audiovisual clip.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] This number is also used in the filename of an associated clip information file "*zzzzz*.clpi".
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] (This number can be a date and time stamp of when the video clip was recorded.) Each stream has its own file.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Files in the AVCHD format use the legacy 8.3 filename convention, whereas Blu-ray discs use long filenames.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] This is why the filename extension of video files is "`.MTS`" instead of Blu-ray disc's "`.m2ts`".
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Also, other files use different extensions: `.CPI` – `.clpi`, `.MPL` – `.mpls`, `.BDM` – `.bdmv`.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] The M2TS files on a Blu-ray disc are placed in the subdirectory "STREAM" of the "BDMV" (or "BDAV") directory, which is at the root level.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] (e.g. \BDMV\STREAM\00001.m2ts or \BDAV\STREAM\00001.m2ts) On some AVCHD equipment, the "BDMV" directory is located in the "AVCHD" directory, which is placed at the root level (e.g. \AVCHD\BDMV\STREAM\00001.MTS).
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Almost all commercially produced Blu-ray disc titles use a copy protection method called the Advanced Access Content System, which encrypts the content of the disc, including M2TS files.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Software that supports M2TS files usually works only with decrypted or unencrypted files.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Blu-ray disc software players can usually play back encrypted content from the original disc.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Video content created using AVCHD equipment is commonly unencrypted.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Most M2TS files can be played with ALLPlayer, MPlayer, VLC, PotPlayer and other media players, depending on the compression formats used in the M2TS file.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Some players will need an appropriate codec, component or plugin installed.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Current versions of Nero Vision, FormatFactory, MediaCoder, HandBrake and Picture Motion Browser are capable of converting M2TS files into MPEG-4 files, which can also be viewed using the aforementioned media players.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] M2TS files can also be played on Sony PlayStation 3s, Sony Bravia TVs, Western Digital WDTVs, Xtreamer media player, Amkette FlashTV HD Media Player and Panasonic Viera TVs supporting playback of AVCHD.
[src:apple-prores/m2ts] Apple's Final Cut Pro can read .MTS files (as stored in Sony HDR camcorders) by using the AVCHD plugin in the Log and Transfer window.
